    lessons: [
      {
        title: "IUPAC Nomenclature",
        content:
          "IUPAC naming follows strict rules. Step 1: find the longest carbon chain (parent chain). Step 2: number from the end closest to the first substituent. Step 3: name substituents as prefixes (methyl, ethyl, bromo, etc.). Step 4: add suffix for the main functional group: alkane (-ane), alkene (-ene), alkyne (-yne), alcohol (-ol), aldehyde (-al), ketone (-one), carboxylic acid (-oic acid). Example: CH₃CH₂CH₂OH = propan-1-ol (3 carbons, OH at C1).",
      },
      {
        title: "Stereochemistry",
        content:
          "Stereoisomers have the same connectivity but different spatial arrangement. Enantiomers are non-superimposable mirror images (chiral centres). A molecule is chiral if it has a carbon bonded to four different groups. R/S configuration is assigned using Cahn-Ingold-Prelog (CIP) priority rules. Diastereomers are stereoisomers that are not mirror images. Geometric isomers (cis/trans or E/Z) occur around C=C double bonds when each carbon bears two different groups.",
      },
      {
        title: "Substitution Reactions",
        content:
          "SN1 (unimolecular nucleophilic substitution): first-order kinetics, proceeds via a carbocation intermediate, favoured by tertiary substrates and polar protic solvents, gives racemisation. SN2 (bimolecular): second-order kinetics, single-step backside attack, favoured by primary substrates and polar aprotic solvents (DMF, DMSO), gives inversion of configuration (Walden inversion). The leaving group ability order: I⁻ > Br⁻ > Cl⁻ >> F⁻.",
      },
      {
        title: "Elimination & Addition Reactions",
        content:
          "E1 and E2 eliminations compete with SN1/SN2. E2 is favoured by strong bulky bases (e.g., t-BuOK) and follows Zaitsev's rule (more substituted alkene preferred) or Hofmann rule with bulky bases. Addition reactions occur across double bonds. Markovnikov's rule: in HX addition, H adds to the less substituted carbon (more substituted carbocation intermediate). Anti-Markovnikov addition occurs with radicals (HBr + peroxide). Bromine (Br₂) adds anti across the double bond (anti addition).",
      },
    ],
